% Motivation
Latin Americanists have several theories to explain the causes and consequences of state capacities. However, most explanations do not consider within-country variations in levels of state capacity.\footnote{For instance, \citet[2368]{Acemoglu2014} explain that there is only ``a small literature on within-country variation in state capacity.'' See for an exception \citet{Foa2016} and \citet{Soifer2008a}.} Since state authorities in less developed countries face higher difficulties achieving political control,\footnote{\citet{Migdal:1988nr}.} this is very unfortunate. Moreover, \emph{domestic} explanations of state-capacities centered on the role of economic-sectoral conflicts, the economic structural transformation and taxation, have been overlooked.\footnote{A few exceptions are \citet[7-8]{Gallo:1991kx}, \citet{Beramendi2016} and \citet[8]{Saylor:2014aa} who consider elite conflicts to study state-making and fiscal development in the developing world. \citet{Dargent2017} focus on a ```challenger-based' causal mechanism'' of state formation in Peru, however they concentrate their efforts on the role of exogenous economic shocks.} For instance, \citet[2]{Schneider:2012rr} explains that even when we have gained considerable knowledge of fiscal expansion in the European cases, the study of the public finances within a context of state-formation in the developing world is lacking, especially in the presence of ``new leading sectors.'' Since wars in Latin America have been rare,\footnote{\citet{Centeno:2002qf}.} it is difficult to extend models developed to understanding the medieval European case based on external threats.\footnote{Some examples are \citet{Tilly:1992rr} and \citet{Dincecco2016}. See however \citet{Thies2005a,Thies2016}.} Critically, there exists in the literature a huge concept-measurement deficit. While most state formation theories (just to name a few) are situated during precolonial,\footnote{\citet{Mahoney:2010aa}.} early,\footnote{See \citet[]{Kurtz:2013aa} and \citet[]{Soifer2015a}.} or late\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ab}.} independent Latin America, we lack of a measurement that corresponds \emph{temporally} to the theories we have. In other words, most explanations of state-making are \emph{historical} in nature. Yet, in practice, available measurements capture \emph{contemporary} levels of \emph{stateness}. In this paper I try to bridge this gap by providing an additional explanation of state capacities in Latin America centered on domestic sectoral economic conflicts and fiscal expansion. Additionally, I provide a corresponding indicator able to capture levels of state capacities \emph{over time} using a novel dataset and approach. The paper then seeks to contribute to the state formation literature in general, both from theoretical and methodological perspectives. 




