% argument and main findings
The central argument of this paper is that higher levels of sectoral contestation characterized by the emergence of a strong industrial sector promoted state-capacities. In particular, the paper explains how higher levels of sectoral contestation promoted the implementation of the income tax, an institution that---according to the fiscal sociology approach---produced positive externalities for state-making. Exploiting the exogeneity of earthquake shocks, I leverage a novel hand-collected dataset on Chilean earthquake death tolls between 1900 and 2010. In conjunction with Bayesian multilevel Poisson models with year fixed-effects, I am able to estimate Chilean state capacities over time. I find that death-tolls decreased (\emph{state capacities increased}) when (1) levels of national/subnational sectoral contestation were high, and (2) after the income tax law was implemented.


% the capacity the state has of enforcing and monitoring building codes throughout the territory is a \emph{reflection} of Chile's 
Under reasonable assumptions, the state's capacity for enforcing and monitoring building codes throughout the territory is a \emph{reflection} of Chile's \emph{overall} state capacities. Earthquakes are time-invariant and, importantly, orthogonal to economic development and regime type. Consequently, death-toll differentials should only be associated with state-capacities. The proposed measurement goes in line with other attempts to capture state capacities over time. While most strategies have focused on the capacity to enforce private contracts,\footnote{See \citet[1]{Besley2010} for an example.} unfortunately, these measurements correlate strongly with property-rights protection, distorting the resemblance between concept and measurement. 

% subnational
The theory also incorporates important subnational dynamics. The ability of the central level to enforce these (and other) institutions depends on whether subnational elites are willing to cooperate with the central level. The paper contends that industrial elites challenged agricultural elites, moving forward investments in state-\emph{making} institutions---the income tax law.\footnote{\citet[208]{Besley2013a} also consider implementing the income tax a strong sign of fiscal capacities, including Chile.} The tax not only increased national revenues, but also helped to form bureaucratic structures at the subnational level. As the Chilean case illustrates, industrial elites were willing to impose a national income tax on themselves in exchange for public goods delivered at the subnational level, and incorporation into the national project. Compliance depended on sustained national--subnational coordination, boosting state centralization.


% The rest of the paper proceeds as follows.
The rest of the paper proceeds as follows. In \autoref{argument} I explain the argument, paying special attention to how the implementation of the income tax expanded state-capacities. Then, in \autoref{chile:section} I illustrate the causal mechanisms at work, presenting some historical context about the Chilean case. In \autoref{measurement} I introduce the proposed measurement and explain how it maps onto state capacities. Then, in \autoref{models}, I present a number of econometric tests. In \autoref{discussion} I provide final comments. In \autoref{appendix} (online appendix) I show some convergence diagnostics.


\section{Sectoral Conflict, Cooperation, and the Case of the Income Tax \label{argument}}

% conflict
The crux of the argument is that sectoral conflicts triggered state development. Analytically, the paper considers that the sectoral conflict approach also offers a theory of state consolidation.\footnote{For a similar view, see \citet[7-8]{Gallo:1991kx}, \citet{Beramendi2016} and \citet[8]{Saylor:2014aa}. Critically, \citet[2]{Schneider:2012rr} explains that even when we have gained considerable knowledge of fiscal expansion in the European cases, the study of developing countries is lacking especially in the presence of `new leading sectors.'} In particular, elites whose assets are allocated in different sectors of the economy have different preferences over state centralization and direct taxation. Consequently, sectoral economic expansion not only (re)shaped the economic landscape; given that both sectors had their corresponding political arms, the \emph{political} conflict over state centralization was rooted in a broader \emph{economic} conflict.\footnote{See \citet{Ansell:2014ty}.} This line of argumentation goes in line with others, in that ``state formation will be most likely to the degree that powerful individual actors form two groups on the basis of divergent economic and political interests.''\footnote{\citet[1085]{Hechter1980a}. Unlike \citet[206]{Besley2013a}, I find that conflict (`political frictions') is not `exogenous,' but rather endogenous to the implementation of the tax itself.} 




% subnational
The capacity of enforcing and monitoring building codes depends on both \emph{national} and \emph{subnational} sources of cooperation, and hence, state incorporation. \citet[1359]{ODonnell1993} famously distinguished different levels of state penetration \emph{in the same country}. The subnational approach goes in line with \citet[103]{Snyder2001}, \citet[286]{Ziblatt2008} and, particularly, \citet[]{Soifer2008a}. Following these important contributions, I implement an identification strategy that not only accounts for temporal but also for geographical---i.e., subnational---sources of sectoral contestation and state capacities. The paper proposes that higher levels of subnational sectoral contestation translated into more credible threats coming from the provinces. Should these subnational sources of contestation \emph{not} be translated into sectoral agreements, the country risked being torn apart or, alternatively, seeing the emergence of local \emph{caudillos} or other regional `bosses.'  For example, the historian \citet[500]{Barros:1970aa} explains that before the civil war, \emph{salitreras} (nitrate towns) in northern Chile were locally so important that they were considered ``a state within the state.''\footnote{My translation.} Local bosses had to approve decisions on whether public employees could be fired, whether public works could be developed, and on whether politicians could give public speeches. Moreover, they coined their own currency and had their own particular local laws. The paper sketches a theory that explains how these national--subnational tensions fostered institutional investments that promoted state capacities over time. 


% elite incorporation
Elite incorporation was possible, contingent on outsiders' capacity for challenging the institutional order that permitted hegemonic groups to rule without opposition. The landed Latin American elites were an economic hegemonic group protected by norms and institutions that originated during colonial times. By extension, the landowning class controlled most of the politics too.\footnote{See for the Chilean case \citet[13]{Zeitlin:1984aa}, \citet[45]{Bauer:2008kx}, \citet[1748]{Baland2008} and \citet[56]{Best1976}, \citet{Rippy:1971rz} and \citet{Marichal:1989bh}.} However, when the \emph{structural transformation} (that is, the ``secular decline of agriculture and substantial expansion of manufacturing'')\footnote{\citet[567]{Johnston1961}.} took place, this process imposed tight constraints on the way politics was run by the incumbent landowning class.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ab}.} Given the initial advantage of the landed elites, the secular emergence of the industrial sector translated into lower levels of inter-sectoral inequality, generating political, economic, and military threats to the landed elites.\footnote{\citet{Boix:2015aa}. For example, elites could use a faction of the existing army or hire private militias.} The higher the threats, the more likely the inter-sectoral compromises (yellow box in \autoref{causal:mechanism:fig}). One particular compromise is identified---the implementation of the income tax---and special attention is paid to how this institution expanded state-capacities overtime. 


% from conflict to compromise: income tax
Since state centralization affects landowners and industrialists in different ways, both sectors have different preferences towards taxation and state centralization.\footnote{See \citet[289]{Acemoglu:1996rm} and \citet[50]{Best1976}.} On the one hand, land fixity increases the risk premium of the landed elite's main asset,\footnote{\citet[512]{Robinson2006a}.} so they systematically resist taxation. In turn, as capital can be reinvested in nontaxable sectors,\footnote{\citet[]{Hirschman:1970bl}. See Ronald Rogowski in \citet[ch. 4]{Drake:1998pi}. However, see \citet[15]{Bates1985}.} industrialists' preferences toward taxation are more elastic. These cross-sectoral tensions are most likely to be resolved in favor of inter-sectoral cooperation---particularly, implementing the income tax law---when income inequality among the elites is low.\footnote{\citet[157]{Tani1966} explains that the absence of ``wealth groups'' makes passing an income tax law easier.} In Latin America, the post-colonial institutional and economical orders were designed to give an unfair advantage to the agricultural sector.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017aa}.} However, the emergence of a strong industrial class led to heavier pressures for higher levels of state centralization and investment in public goods at the local level. I find elsewhere that the emergence of the industrial sector \emph{accelerated} the implementation of the income tax in a number of Latin American states.\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017ab}.} In fact, it was not only sustained industrial expansion that depended on the implementation of the income tax. \citet[18]{Beramendi2016} explain that, as industrialists depended more on infrastructure implemented at the local level, such as roads, railroads, and bridges, they ``[\emph{preferred}] to shoulder a higher tax burden through progressive direct taxation.'' But also, lower levels of inter-elite economic inequality implied similar degrees of military capabilities.\footnote{\citet{Boix:2015aa}.} Under these circumstances, war was most likely to exhaust all existent assets without producing positive outcomes for either sector,\footnote{Richard Salvucci in \citet[48]{Uribe-Uran:2001aa}.} leading to heavier pressures to reach agreements instead of engaging in armed conflicts. 



% income tax --> positive externalities of income taxation (0)
However, the tax was not only important because of the new revenue it collected. While Humud (1969, p. 154) explains that the income tax generated considerable resources for the Chilean treasury,\footnote{\citet[451-452]{Bowman1982}.} following the fiscal sociology paradigm, the tax was also important for state-making. \citet[99]{Musgrave1992} argues that since taxation (especially on incomes) requires such a high degree of state penetration, public finances offer the key for a theory of state-building. Indirect taxes are easier to levy, and, hence, this kind of revenue is generally considered ``unearned income''\footnote{\citet[304]{Moore2004a}.} or ``easy-to-collect source of revenues.''\footnote{\citet[10]{Coatsworth2002}.} Given the relatively lower costs states have to incur to collect them, indirect taxes have a very low impact on state-building.\footnote{\citet[14]{Moore2004}.} For example, \citet[46]{Krasner:1985lq} explains that ``tariffs and export taxes are easier to obtain than direct taxes, which require high levels of bureaucratic skill and voluntary compliance.'' In fact, when early Latin American states depended heavily on trade taxes, the state apparatus tended to be less developed.\footnote{\citet[177]{Campbell1993}.} Since customs administrations have always been concentrated in a few critical locations, especially ports, tariffs and customs duties did not require an elaborate fiscal structure.\footnote{\citet[132]{Bertola2012}.} 


% income tax --> positive externalities of income taxation (1)
The very implementation of the income tax produced a secular accumulation of know-how, particularly of better technologies able to monitor individual incomes. Unlike `regular' institutions, income taxation enables the state's coercive sovereignty to infiltrate the individuals themselves. Not only observing individual economies, but transforming them into public property is what fostered state expansion.\footnote{\citet[98]{Musgrave1992} and \citet[298]{Moore2004a}. While \citet{Kurtz2009,Kurtz:2013aa,Soifer2015a} situate the relevant state-building critical juncture at the end of the colonial period, before the class compromises I identify in this paper, I argue that the implementation of the income tax was an important building block in this process.} This argument goes in line with \citet{Besley2013a}, who explain that implementing the income tax law is ``associated with investments in public administrative structures that support tax collection'' in a number of countries, including Chile. I contend that the knowledge and expertise the state accumulated were transferred to other state institutions via spillovers, augmenting the overall levels of \emph{stateness}. As \citet[1]{Levi:1989lq} explains, ``the history of state revenue production is the history of of the evolution of the state.'' For instance, it was necessary to send official emissaries to check on accounting books of the refinery in the north, the winery in the central valley, and the \emph{hacienda} in the south. Eventually, these delegations became more complex, increasing the density of state presence in the territory. For instance, \citet{Strayer:2005uq} explains how official state delegations traveled the territory dispensing judicial decisions, thereby fostering state centralization. Furthermore, \citet{Dincecco2015} explains that states became effective organisms upon centralizing a system of direct taxation and implementing some kind of checks-and-balances system. As I explain in \autoref{chile:section}, the Chilean case met these two conditions. Others find that the \emph{introduction} of the income tax is associated with state expansion too. For instance, \citet[3]{Dincecco2015a} find ``a positive and significant relationship between the introduction of the income tax and (1) per capita total expenditures, (2) per capita education expenditures, and (3) per capita health expenditures.'' Analytically, the \emph{effectiveness} of income taxation on fiscal \emph{capacities} increased due to the nature of the implementation of the income tax. \citet[566]{Aghion2004} explain how optimal institutional choices result from political settings where all involved actors ``had a voice in the choice of institutions,'' essentially contributing to an equilibrium of quasi-voluntary compliance.\footnote{\citet{Levi:1989lq}.} In line with this literature, I find in \autoref{chile:section} that \emph{both} elites agreed on imposing the tax on themselves. 


%
Finally, income taxation did more than just triggering other state capacities. Via a process of assimilation, it also helped in constructing the figure of the \emph{citizen} centered around the concept of the \emph{taxpayer}. Regardless of an individual's race, religion, culture, or any other kind of status, the state classifies its subjects according to their incomes and obliges them to pay, punishing whoever refuses to do so. From a sociological standpoint, this ``generality makes taxation a crucial element in the development of the `imagined community'\footnote{\citet[]{Anderson2006a}.} of the modern nation-state [...] Taxation enmeshes us in the web of generalized reciprocity that constitutes modern society.''\footnote{Martin et al. (in \citet[3]{Martin2009a}).}


\section{Historical Background\label{chile:section}}

% Historians still debate whether agriculturalists and industrialists comprised two different elites
Historians still debate whether agriculturalists and industrialists comprised two \emph{different} elites. Some claim that this dualism is incorrect.\footnote{\citet[125]{Mamalakis:1976kx}.} They argue that, since landowners also invested in industry,\footnote{\citet[57, 95]{Kirsch:1977aa} who cites \citet[]{Bauer:2008kx}. See also \citet[23]{Coatsworth2002} argue that ``[t]he only landowners that mattered in 19th century Latin American politics were those for whom land represented but one asset in a much broader portfolio.'' In the same vein, \citet[180]{Bauer:2008kx} argues that ``[m]iners and merchants bought haciendas but landowners in turn invested in banks, insurance companies, commercial firms and the incipient industrial sector.''} there was a blurry class division between the mining, banking, and agricultural sectors.\footnote{\citet[30, 44, 94, 108]{Bauer:2008kx}.} Perhaps the most cited reference regarding this issue is \citet[231-247]{Veliz1963}. I contend that there are a series of stylized facts that strongly suggest that there was indeed a structural economic cleavage, which led to the consolidation of  two separate sectors. First of all, there were certain practices that mask the existence of a  sectoral dualism. For example, it was common that industrialists invested in real estate. However, in many instances they did so \emph{just} to obtain credit. \citet[59]{Kirsch:1977aa} explains that ``in a \emph{rural society} land offered one of the best guarantees for loans [since] loans could not be secured by equipment, machinery, or inventory. Only real estate was acceptable collateral.''\footnote{Emphases are mine.} In fact, this practice shows how the credit system was oriented to give unfair advantage to the landed elites. Similarly, \citet[174]{Zeitlin:1984aa} finds ``the combined ownership of capital and landed property was a distinctive quality of \emph{certain} [elites] actors,''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} not something that was generalizable to \emph{the} elites. There were also other instances where miners invested in banking. Yet, \citet{Segall1953} argues that Chilean bankers, after the crisis of the mining sector around the 1870s, had acquired a number of mineral deposits given as collateral years before. Similarly, but for the Argentinean case, \citet[609]{Hora2002} explains that ``the image of an entrepreneurial elite with assets \emph{scattered throughout several spheres of investment} does not appear entirely correct.''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} In fact, \citet{Freeman2012} explains that while most political development theories run short due to their purely domestic nature, asset diversification constitutes a later development ``in international markets [roughly after 1980].'' I contend that the nature of the main factors of production of agriculturalists and industrialists (land v. capital), in addition to their preferences regarding fiscal policy, produced a strong sectoral cleavage. In fact, borrowing from the Lewis model of economic growth, I explain elsewhere that the agricultural sector's role in the economy is to supply labor to the industrial sector, limiting agriculture's expansion relative to industry's growth,\footnote{\citet{Bahamonde:2017aa}.} evidencing the lack of incentives for crossed investments.





