% there are two elites.
In all Latin American economies during and after the colonial period, agriculture was the most important sector.\footnote{\citet[13]{Keller1931}.} Thus, by extension, agricultural political elites were the most powerful group.\footnote{\citet[45-46]{Wright1975}.} \citet[106]{Collier:2002db} explain that the ``national government was dominated by the central part of the country, with owners of large agricultural holdings playing a predominant role.''\footnote{Similarly, \citet[15]{McBride:1971fv} explains that ``Chile's people live on the soil. Her life is agricultural to the core. \emph{Her government has always been of farm owners. Her Congress is made up chiefly of rich landlords}. Social life is dominated by families whose proudest possession is the ancestral estate.'' Emphases are mine.} However, an important asymmetry existed. While both the agricultural and industrial sectors were growing at the same pace (see \autoref{fig:incometax}, top panel), the latter were kept from participating in politics under fair conditions.\footnote{For instance, \citet{Bahamonde:2017ab} explains that President Balmaceda's agenda on ``industrial'' infrastructure (mainly roads and railroads) mostly benefited agricultural areas, and that his attitude towards the banking sector (closely linked to the mining sector) was mostly confiscatory. See especially \citet[]{Zeitlin:1984aa}.} Initially, this asymmetry led these two ``antagonistic elites''\footnote{\citet[37-38]{Keller1931}.} to two bloody civil wars. \citet[23]{Zeitlin:1984aa} argues that the civil wars challenged a ``large landed property [elite against a] productive capital[ist] [elite].'' Due to low levels of inequality (and similar military capacities) war was not sustainable over time. For instance, while \emph{Balmacedistas} managed to secure the support of the army, \emph{congresistas} (the anti-Balmaceda group) gathered support from the navy. Similarly, in the subsequent years of the civil war, there were a number of \emph{aborted} coups, in 1907, 1912, 1915, and 1919,\footnote{\citet[109]{Collier:2002db}.} suggesting an equilibrium where no elite was the leading elite. In 1924, industrial elites accepted to be income taxed by agriculturalist incumbents in exchange for having more \emph{state services} and being included in state politics. As others have explained, the non-agricultural sector ``accepted taxation, \emph{while demanding state services and expecting to influence how tax revenues were spent} [...] \emph{Consultation and cooperation were relatively institutionalised between the two sides}.''\footnote{Carmenza Gallo, in \citet[165]{Brautigam2008}. Emphases are mine.} As explained above, income taxation did more than just increasing the treasury's budget. Importantly, these sectoral compromises increased the complexity of the state, expanding its dominion beyond Santiago. Moreover, it allowed previously-excluded (industrial) elites to influence public spending. \emph{Did sectoral contestation increase state capacities? Did implementing the income tax increase state capacities over time?}



\section{From Earthquake Death Tolls to State Capacities\label{measurement}}

% different measures
More than being blessed, the literature is in fact cursed with an over-abundance of poor indicators of state capacities.\footnote{\citet[10]{Hanson2013b} compiled 24 different types of measurements of state-capacities. In turn \citet{Mata2009} constructed a combined measurement of 12 other indicators.} \citet[589]{Soifer2012} explains that there exists an ``industry of indices measuring state weakness, state failure, and state fragility [which] has cropped up in recent years.'' Yet, as \citet[347]{Fukuyama2013} argues, its abundance ``points to the poor state of empirical measures of the quality of states.'' The literature points to two major concerns. First, ``most fragility indices barely satisfy scientific standards''\footnote{\citet[35]{Mata2009}. They point out particularly to the fact that data are usually poor.} and, second, most indices are conflated with analytical and conceptual problems.\footnote{I agree with \citet[586]{Soifer2012} in that most ``scholarship on state capacity [...] lack[s] a satisfying conceptualization and measurement scheme for this concept.'' See also \citet[1292]{Ferreira2017}.} One notable example is protection of the rule of law, which is commonly used as proxy for state capacities.\footnote{See for one example \citet[1237]{Besley2009}.} As \citet[543]{Kurtz2007} explain, this strategy is severely confounded ``with policy preferences over the structure of private property rights.'' On the one hand, this is problematic, since the sources of this data are usually elite interviews. To ``the extent that public bureaucracies \emph{are} effective in imposing taxes or regulatory demands [...] they are likely to be judged `burdensome' and `growth-inhibiting' by many businesspersons,''\footnote{\citet[542]{Kurtz2007}. Emphasis in original.} thereby introducing systematic measurement error.\footnote{See also \citet[618]{Kurtz2012}.} Likewise, expert surveys suffer from the same problem.\footnote{\citet[349]{Fukuyama2013}.} On the other hand, the problem is conceptual. As \citet[247]{Soifer2008a} puts it, there is a widely spread ``problem of misalignment between dimension and indicator.'' \citet[619]{Kurtz2012} recommend ``explicitly avoid[ing] an emphasis on outputs that are at the center of political or policy debates, such as property rights.'' For example, the U.S.S.R. had a strong state, however it did \emph{not} protect property rights. Another example has to do with the indicators provided by the World Bank. These series are ``[c]learly, the most comprehensive source for cross-national measures of governance.''\footnote{\citet[543]{Kurtz2007}.} They consider absence of violence, among other factors. However, ``there isn't much by way of street crime or military coup attempts in North Korea,''\footnote{\citet[348]{Fukuyama2013}.} a state that can barely provide basic services to its population. Focusing on tax rates is not a solution either.\footnote{Yet, \citet[3]{Johnson2017} explain that `[t]ax revenue per capita is a commonly used metric of fiscal capacity,' which in turn might work as a proxy of state capacities. For example, \citet{Besley2014} adopt this strategy.} For example, in late imperial China, ``high taxes on peasants [...] were the result of rulers' lack of power. Chinese rulers consistently attempted to limit official's excessive extractions from the masses, but were unable to do so.''\footnote{\citet[301]{Kiser1992}.}



% temporal
This paper identifies a third limitation. Beyond conceptual and analytical problems, most available measurements are unable to capture temporal sources of variation of state capacities. Since most explanations of state-making have a strong historical component, the lack of an indicator able to `travel in time' represents a huge deficit in the literature. Just to name a few examples, \citet[585]{Soifer2012} ``builds a new measure of state capacity for [...] \emph{contemporary} Latin America [combining] multiple dimensions (extraction, security, and the administration of basic services).''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} \citet[618-619]{Kurtz2012} propose an experimental design based on list-experiments to study (in an unbiased way) bureaucrat's opinions, \citet{Dargent2017} ``analyzes the evolution of state capacity in Peru during the \emph{recent} commodity boom,''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} while \citet{Luna2014,Luna2017} employ a survey-based design to measure \emph{contemporary} subnational state capacities. While these measurements overcome the conceptual and analytical problems mentioned above, they do not help us in studying state capacities in a historical setup. Economic historians and other students of political development offer other alternatives. Some examples are levels of investments in public goods,\footnote{\citet{Enriquez2017}.} such as infrastructure, roads,\footnote{\citet{Mann1984a,Mann2008a,Acemoglu2005a,Saylor2012,Thies2009,Besley2010}.} electrification (measured as light intensity per pixel),\footnote{\citet{Huntington2014}.} and railroads.\footnote{\citet[302]{Saylor2012} and \citet{Coatsworth1974a}.} However, many of these measurements are debatable. For instance, \citet[593]{Soifer2012} explains that ``railroads were often constructed by private actors.''\footnote{Footnote \#11.} The same problem applies to other types of infrastructure. There are others more appropriate strategies, such as the opening of postal offices,\footnote{\citet{Robinson2016}.} the administration of national censuses,\footnote{\citet{Lee2017}, \citet{Soifer2013a} and \citet{Centeno:2002qf}. This technique is borrowed from demographers. It compares the age structure (incorrectly) captured in the census with an assumed `correct' theoretical age distribution. Low-capacity states should inaccurately round ages or inflate certain intervals, producing error. The error is usually computed using the Whipple's index which serves as a proxy for state capacities.} and vaccination.\footnote{\citet{Soifer2012}.} While these measurements do capture historical variations of state capacities, some other problems arise. Censuses, for example, provide a \emph{non-continuous temporal measurement} of state capacities. For instance, censuses are applied in Chile every ten years. Having just a few snapshots of state-capacity should compromise any statistical analysis. In turn, vaccines are usually targeted at primary and high school students. In practice, vaccines are administered by the schools themselves, both public and private. Private schools might be more efficient in doing so, inflating the \emph{average} level of state-capacity. 



%Others have used economic growth,\footnote{\citet{Fearon2003} and \citet{Besley:2011aa}.}\todo{Mahoney?} which is also problematic.\todo{explain why} Dargent2017 explain why.


% my measurement
To solve some of these limitations, the paper proposes considering earthquake death tolls as an alternative to measure state capacities over time. Unlike censuses---\emph{unfortunately}--- earthquakes happen in Chile very often. While ``[e]arthquakes alone claim thousands of lives a year,''\footnote{\citet[1908]{Anbarci2005}.} they are not well studied in the discipline.\footnote{\citet[719]{Brancati2007} explains that ``[d]isasters are not as well studied [...] in the field of political science.''} Building on \citet[113]{Mann1984a}, the proposed measurement intends to capture the state's `infrastructural' power.\footnote{He defines infrastructural power as  ``the capacity of the state [to] actually [...] penetrate civil society, and to implement logistically political decisions throughout the realm.''} ``Natural hazards can be seen as a function of a specific natural process and human [...] activity.''\footnote{\citet[627]{Raschky2008}.} Given that earthquakes happen at random and are exogenous to the affected locality,\footnote{\citet[728]{Brancati2007} explains that ``earthquakes constitute a natural experiment.'' \citet[27]{Gignoux2016} also point out ``that the occurrence of earthquakes can be viewed as random [allowing the analyses of] these events as a set of repeated social experiments.'' \citet[32, unpublished]{Caruso2017}, for instance, ``[exploits] the exogenous variation in the location and timing of natural disasters.''} the only part that is left unexplained is the systematic human component, which is what the proposed measurement captures. Earthquakes are orthogonal to levels of state capacity and economic development.\footnote{\citet[271]{Kahn2005} and \citet{Brancati2007}.} Thus, keeping earthquake magnitudes constant at their means, (population-weighted) death counts should be attributed to the (\emph{in})capacity of the states to invest in preparedness and earthquake-mitigation institutions.\footnote{To make sure, while ``earthquakes may not be preventable, it is possible to prevent the disasters they cause'' (\citet[209]{Escaleras2007}). Similarly, \citet[1911]{Anbarci2005} explain that ``the potentially devastating effects of major earthquakes are, if not preventable, at least subject to significant mitigation.'' For a similar approach, see \citet[130]{Noji:1996aa}.} I focus on earthquakes and not on other natural disasters, such as ``extreme temperature events, floods, landslides, and windstorms,''\footnote{\citet[280]{Kahn2005}.} because earthquakes cannot be foreseen and, as such, they put to test the states' capacity for having their preventive institutions \emph{already} in place and in good shape.\footnote{In fact, \citet[716]{Brancati2007} explains that ``[e]arthquakes may provoke conflict more than any other type of natural disaster \emph{because} they have rapid onsets [and] are not predictable.'' Emphasis is mine.} State capacities consist of sustained \emph{proactive} efforts of enforcing institutions in the territory, and, hence, short-term \emph{reactive} actions should \emph{not} be considered state-\emph{making}. 



% preparedeness // construction
Under reasonable assumptions, the capacity states have in deploying inspectors to enforce quake-sensitive zoning and building codes should be a reflection of the overall levels of state capacity. Since ``[e]arthquake-resistant construction depends on responsible governance,''\footnote{\citet[153]{Ambraseys2011}. Similarly, \citet[628]{Raschky2008} argue that ``the effects of natural hazards [do] not solely depend on a region's topographic or climatic exposure to natural processes [...] but [on] the region's \emph{institutional} vulnerability.'' Emphasis is mine.} state capacities act as a scope condition, in particular, undermining (or facilitating) the implementation of these norms. For example, \citet[169]{Bilham2013} explains that ``although engineering codes may \emph{exist}[,] mechanisms to \emph{implement} these codes are largely unavailable''\footnote{Emphases are mine.} in low-capacity states. For example, \citet[1910]{Anbarci2005} explain that ``while Iran has building codes [...] comparable to those existing in the United States, they tend to be enforced only in the country's larger cities,'' failing to monitor the countryside, which was where most casualties occurred in the magnitude 6.4 earthquake in Changureh in 2002.\footnote{Similarly, \citet[865]{Bardhan2016} explains that ``unlike in the case of some macroeconomic policies, [...] the effectiveness of the state varies enormously across localities and administrative levels within the same country.''} Importantly, the proposed measurement bridges this gap by incorporating and modeling the capacity for enforcing these codes at the subnational level. 

% marco legal
Only high-capacity states overcome their own limitations, not only implementing but also enforcing quake-sensitive regulations. The Chilean government started its efforts to ameliorate the impact of earthquakes after the great quake of 1928 in Talca. A first effort happened in 1929, when \href{http://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idNorma=149306}{\emph{Ley} number 4563} was implemented. The law was among the first attempts to prohibit ``construction, reconstruction or any other repairing or transformations [...] without a permit from the authorities.'' Importantly, the law required that all blueprints had to be signed off by an expert before the construction started. By 1930, \href{https://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idNorma=1038437&idParte=0&idVersion=}{\emph{Decreto} number 4882} was adopted, but this time the rule made a number of technical prescriptions,\footnote{See especially article 151.} determining what kinds of construction materials ought to be used, among other requirements. Critically, while the central government had retained the control of the supervision of the code since the promulgation of the \emph{ley}, the \emph{decreto} explicitly created the role of the \emph{inspector} to supervise, enforce, and monitor these measures at the local level. Furthermore, \emph{art\'iculo} 414 of the Chilean \emph{Decreto} 4882 granted inspectors ``free access to the building'' at any time during the construction process. The proposed measurement picks up whether these good intentions written in paper actually achieved lower death tolls.

% basic social contract
Earthquake damage poses a major threat to commercial, official, and residential buildings, potentially triggering higher levels of looting and social unrest. Consequently, enforcing quake-sensitive building codes also embodies the most basic form of social contract that exists between the state and its subjects. Any kind of political leader should be interested in preventing looting and social unrest. Leaders not only care about their own survival (\emph{electoral or not}) but also about the legitimacy of `the state.' In the event of heavy social unrest, not only is the essential social Hobbesian-like contract broken but the expectations of social peace are also questioned.\footnote{\citet[419]{Carlin2014a} study how earthquakes damage interpersonal trust. They argue that ``state capacity plays a decisive role in determining natural disasters' consequences for social capital.''} The physical presence of the state literally \emph{crumbles} when institutions of social coercion and discipline, such as state schools, prisons, and police stations, collapse. For example, when the magnitude 7.0 earthquake hit Hati in 2010, the \emph{Prison Civile de Port-au-Prince} had a population of 4,500 inmates. During the quake, five inmates died. As a prison guard describes it, ``everyone escaped. Everyone. Except the dead.'' This natural disaster exacerbated the already existent chaos, freeing ``gang bosses, kidnappers, gunmen,'' among others,\footnote{\citet{Reed:2011}. See also \citet{Laursen2010}.} reducing the legitimacy of the state to zero.


% advantages // it's objective and subnational
The proposed measurement has a number of advantages. Unlike non-experimental survey-based or purely policy-based measures, earthquake death tolls are an \emph{objective} measurement of earthquake preparedness,\footnote{That is, ``it does not rely on an effort to measure the beliefs of citizens about the nature of the state, the legitimacy of its leaders or the institutional procedures that selected them, or even perceptions of the efficiency of public bureaucracies'' (\citet[616]{Kurtz2012}).} an activity that \emph{any} state \emph{must} perform.\footnote{To be sure, any state susceptible to earthquakes. \citet[58]{Kurtz:2013aa} for example explains that ``the best measures [of state capacities] would be of the sorts of activities that all (or nearly all) states consider to be of primary importance.'' Similarly, \citet[422]{Carlin2014a} explain that ``a basket of `minimal' state functions [typically includes] primary education, public health, rule of law, public finance management, and disaster relief.''} Importantly, \citet[235-236]{Soifer2008a} divides the state infrastructural power into three layers, `national capabilities,'\footnote{This layer `sees state infrastructural power as a characteristic of the central state'.} the `weight of the state,'\footnote{This relates to `how the exercise of state power shapes the society it controls.'} and a `subnational' component, which tracks ``the ability of the state to exercise control within its territory.'' The proposed measurement strategy maps well onto all three components. 


% This measurement has a number of drawbacks
However, the measurement has a number of drawbacks. Obviously, the country needs to have earthquakes, possibly limiting the number of potential cases. However, most ``earthquakes occur at the various borders of the Pacific plate, the Western border of the Latin American plate, and the boundaries between the African, the Arabic and the Indian plates and the Eurasian plate,'' allowing potential cross-country comparisons within most of the developing world.\footnote{\citet[1534]{Keefer2011}. From a population size perspective, this measurement is also convenient. A ``quarter of the world's population inhabits [...] the northern edge of the Arabian and Indian Plates that are colliding with the southern margin of the Eurasian Plate'' (\citet[618]{Bilham2013a}). Other measurements are also context-specific. For example, \citet[593]{Soifer2012} proposes a measurement of administrative capacities focusing on how states are able to enforce voter registration ``where voting is mandatory.''} Moreover, there are countries, like India or the United States, where earthquakes happen in certain regions only. Presumably, mitigation policies in these places would need to be targeted to specific areas, possibly undermining the assumption that these kinds of policies should penetrate the `entire' territory.\footnote{\citet[164]{Dunbar2003} explains that the Indian state implements targeted policies (that might not necessarily correspond to the administrative areas) based on isoseismal maps that define different zones of seismic hazard.} Another potential concern is that the ability of counting the death-toll might be a function of state capacities itself.\footnote{I thank Paul Poast for this comment.} However, in most cases, civic organizations, the Catholic Church, and, particularly, the press (national and local) have been the main entities who (willingly or not) have carried out the task of enumerating the deaths. Another potential issue is the measurement of the magnitudes. Before the instrumental period, magnitudes were obtained in an estimative way, and, while there are methods to approximate historically-felt magnitudes to instrumental-like intensities,\footnote{\citet{Szeliga2010}.} this strategy unfortunately adds more than one layer of complexity. All in all, this measurement offers a rough approximation of levels of state capacities over time.



\section{Multilevel Analyses\label{models}}


% explain dataset
I constructed a hand-collected novel dataset using the \emph{Significant Earthquake Database} compiled by the National Centers for Environmental Information (NOAA) as a starting point.\footnote{\citet[]{noaa2015}.} The dataset ``contains information on destructive earthquakes from 2150 B.C. to the present,'' and records the number of deaths,\footnote{Importantly, the NOAA distinguishes earthquake deaths from total deaths (which includes tsunami casualties). I use the former.} the magnitude, date, latitude, and longitude of every quake, among other variables. Using archival census data from 1907 to 2012,\footnote{Particularly, censuses of 1907, 1920, 1930, 1940, 1952, 1960, 1970, 1982, 1992, 2002 and 2012. Some of them were kept at the \emph{Biblioteca Nacional} and others at the \emph{National Statistic Institute} historical library.} I complemented the NOAA dataset with local population at the municipal level where the quake hit. I use local population to weight the death toll.\footnote{While in most occasions I was able to recover the actual local population, in some instances that was not possible. In these cases, I recovered the population of the most concentrated area nearby. Consequently, I adopted a more general approach and used population as a control, not as a variable to construct a dependent variable in proportion-like form.} Using archival census data as well, I considered the main economic activity of the affected municipality,\footnote{\text{$\Sexpr{levels(factor(datsc$Sector))[1]}$} (n=$\Sexpr{as.character(table(factor(datsc$Sector))[1])}$), \text{$\Sexpr{levels(factor(datsc$Sector))[2]}$} (n=$\Sexpr{as.character(table(factor(datsc$Sector))[2])}$), \text{$\Sexpr{levels(factor(datsc$Sector))[3]}$} (n=$\Sexpr{as.character(table(factor(datsc$Sector))[3])}$).} in addition to whether the municipality was urban or rural.\footnote{Urban=$\Sexpr{table(datsc$Urban[datsc$Urban==1])}$, rural=$\Sexpr{table(datsc$Urban[datsc$Urban==0])}$. If more than 50\% of the population lives in an urban setting, I assigned a 1 to that municipality, 0 otherwise. Urban concentrations are most likely to have vertical constructions rather than one-story buildings, increasing the potential number of casualties. Consequently, it is important to control for this source of variation. I thank Daniel Kelemen for this suggestion.} The death tolls and magnitudes proportionated by the NOAA dataset were contrasted case by case with historical press archival information.\footnote{\emph{El Mercurio} and \emph{La Naci\'on} newspapers, both kept at the \emph{Archivo} of the \emph{Biblioteca Nacional de Chile}.} Magnitudes, in particular, were also compared with the \href{http://www.isc.ac.uk/iscbulletin/search/bulletin/}{International Seismological Centre}. All these are subnational-level variables. Next, I included national-level indicators that aim to serve as proxies for levels of sectoral conflict. Following \citet{Bahamonde:2017ab,Bahamonde:2017aa}, I measured the degree to which the industrial elites challenged incumbent landowners by calculating the proportion of agricultural growth relative to industrial growth as presented in the  \href{http://moxlad-staging.herokuapp.com/home/en?}{MOxLAD} data (see \autoref{fig:incometax}, bottom panel).\footnote{``These data build on the studies and statistical abstracts of the Economic Commission for Latin America, but also rely on Mitchell's International Historical Statistics, International Monetary Fund's International Financial Statistics, the World Bank's World Development Indicators and a variety of national sources.'' I used the \emph{agriculture value-added} and \emph{manufacturing value-added} variables. The former measures ``the output of the sector net of intermediate inputs and includes the cultivation of crops, livestock production, hunting, forestry and fishing.'' The later  ``[r]eports the output of the sector net of intermediate inputs.'' Both of them are expressed in local currency at 1970 constant prices.} According to \citet[790]{Astorga2005}, these data provide extended comparable sectoral value-added series in constant purchasing power parity prices. Even when pre-1900 earthquakes are recorded in both the NOAA data and my own dataset (\autoref{fig:earthquake:ts:plot:chile}), the economic data provided by MOxLAD limits the scope of this paper to the period from $\Sexpr{min(datsc$year)}$ to $\Sexpr{max(datsc$year)}$ (\autoref{fig:incometax}).



