\paragraph{Did taxation improve state capacities overtime?} Following the same setup, I fit a simpler one-dimensional Poisson model. The only complexity kept were the yearly fixed-effects. The main difference is the inclusion of an indicator variable that denotes whether the income tax is implemented by year $t$, and whose estimated parameter ($\beta_{1}$) is the main quantity of interest. 

More formally, I fitted the next equation:


\begin{equation} \label{model:2}
\begin{split}
\text{Deaths} \;\sim\; & \text{Poisson}(\lambda_{i})\\
log(\lambda_{i})  = 
&\;\mu + 
\beta_{1}\text{Income Tax}_{i} + 
\beta_{2}\text{Magnitude}^2_{i} +
\beta_{3}\text{Latitude}_{i} + 
\beta_{4}\text{Longitude}_{i} + \\
& \beta_{5}\text{Population}_{i} +
\beta_{6}\text{Urban}_{i} + 
\beta_{7_t}\text{Year}_{i}
\end{split}
\end{equation}


\autoref{income:tax:model:regression:table:run} also shows posterior predictive distributions. The results show that implementing the income tax \emph{decreases} the death-toll by an estimated average of $\Sexpr{abs(round(reg.results.table.tax$Mean[rownames(reg.results.table.tax) == 'Income Tax'],0))}$. \autoref{fig:income:tax:model:plot:run} shows the effect over time, and how death-tolls (state capacities) \emph{decrease} (increase) over time. Before the income tax law was implemented, death-tolls were relatively stable, averaging approximately 28 casualties per earthquake. However, once the income tax law was implemented, the death-toll decreased from 28 to 22, approximately. 


