Fiscal sociologists have, for a long time, claimed that the capacity of taxing individuals' incomes transfers to other state institutions, improving overall state-capacities. Here, I find support for this claim. Historical evidence suggests that the treasury did increase the Chilean fiscal coffers after the implementation of the income tax law, suggesting a denser (and better) state presence at the local level. My analyses suggest that the act of \emph{sending} bureaucrats to collect the income tax had positive externalities on other state activities. Here I identify one such activity, the enforcement of national quake-sensitive norms. The data analyses show (statistically) that, \emph{ceteris paribus}, state capacities increase over time after the implementation of the income tax law.


	
